neapolis.\nTake home a box of candy occasion\njjs ally to sweeten your wife\u2019s temper.\nWhatever lifts up the heart enlarges\nthe life.\nONLY ONE \u201cBRONO QUININE\"\nThat 1s LAXATIVE BROMO QUININE. J-ook for\ntbe signature of E. W. UKOVE. Usod the World\nover to Cure a Cold in One Hay. 26c.\nFollow your inclination if you like;\nthat\u2019s the road to ruin.\nEvery man knows how other men\nought to do things.\nWhen a woman is ugly she can be\nuglier than a man.\nSICK HEADACHE\nI ICAKTEKSI\u2014\u201c\nThey also relieve Dia\n/jSS&H I'pri r tress from Dyspepsia, In-\nTHT Z. jL digestion and Too Hearty\nISi I t R Fating. A perfect rem*\nIBJu| e edy for Dlxb):j -a, Nutt\n-1 M rILL Va sea, Drowsiness, Bad\n|l_jg Taste i n the M outh, Coat-\nHBEHq ed Tongue, Pain in tbe\nI Side, TORPID LIVER.\nThey regulate the Bowela. Purely Vegetable.\nSMALL PILL SMALL DOSE, SMALL PRICE.\nPADTCDCI Genuine Must Bear\nA UAKItno Fac-Simile Signature\nf ISK\ngjLJ REFUSE SUBSTITUTES.\n1 SPOT GASH\nFOR SOLDIERS AND HEIRS\niAll federal soldiers anil sailors wbo served 90 days\nbetween 1881 and lHflti and wbo homesteaded less than\nKid acres before June 23,1874. are entitled to additional\nhomestead rights which 1 buy. If soldier Isdead, bis\nmg heirs can sell. Talk toold soldiers, widowsand heirs.\nFind some soldier relative who went West or South\nafter the war and homes eaded government land.\nGet busy and make some easy money. Write HKNKT\nN. Cure, Washington. i>. C-. for further particulars.\nVirginia Farms and Homes.\nProductive soil .mild, healthy climate. Splendid markets.\nWrit# for catalog. B.a.CMtIHS SCO .l.t Klrfcw\u2014S.Va.\n(IATPIITA WaiMa C olr.\u00abB, Patent Attop.\npfl I pM I JE ney. Washington, D. Advice\nI HI kail Wires. Terms low. Highest ret.\nI\nI PBI ||j 1111 rlmPrllll M\nV What a B\u00abttler Can Secure In\nI WESTERN CANADA\nI*o Acres Grain-Growing I-s~l FREE.\nSO to 40 Buslmls Wheat to the Aero.\n40 to BO Bushels Oats to the Aero.\n35 to 50 Bushels Barley to the Aero.\nTimber for Fencing and Buildings FREE.\nGood Laws with Low Taxation.\nI Splendid Railroad Facilities and Low Rates.\nI Schools and Churches Convenient.\nSatisfactory Markets for all Productions.\nGood Climate and Perfect Health.\nJ Chances for Profitable Investments.\nI Some of the choicest grain-producing lands In\nJ Saskatchewan and Alberta may now be ac-\nI gulred in theae most healthful and prosperous\nI sections under the\nI Revised Homestead Regulations\nJ by which entry may be made by proxy (on cer\n1\\ tain conditions), by the father, mother, son,\nHA* daughter, brother o* slater of intending home-\nSteader.\nf Entry fee in each ease is 110.00. For pamphlet,\nS \"Last BestWest.\"particulars us to rates,routes,\nS bast time ts go and where to locate, apply to\nI. H. MAC IACHLAH.\nI In Ilf. Watertown, Sesth Baked.\nM-a-MTd-\nSi.\nJIM\nKidneys.\nhips ached and every\nPrejudice.\nPATENTS.\nV-*\nUK j 1 /.'Mil\nf^ongress.\nReturn* of the Week's\nProceedings.\nTuesday.\nWashington, Jan. 8. Senator Aid\nrich yesterday introduced his curren\ncy bill, which has been a subject for\ndiscussion among the members of the\ncommittee on finance for some days.\nHe had the bill read to the senate and\nannounced that the committee would\nbe glad to consider in connection with\nit all bills that senators might desire\nto introduce. He assured Senator Cul\nberson that his resolution would re\nceive attention.\nAt 1:40 the senate adjourned until\nto-morrow to permit more work by\ncommittees.\nThe usual resolution referring the\npresident\u2019s annual message to the sev\neral committees furnished the occa\nsion in the house of representatives\nyesterday for a number of addresses,\nmostly by members on the Democratic\nside. These covered a variety of sub\njects, but those that attracted espe\ncial attention were by Representatives\nSheppard of Texas and Willett of New\nYork. The former not only made a\nplea for the restoration of the legend\n\u201cIn God we trust\u201d on American coins,\nbut discussed the cruise of the Ameri\ncan battleship fleet and referred to a\npossible conflict with Japan.\nMr. Willett placed all the blame for\nthe recent financial panic on Presi\ndent Roosevelt, whom he denounced\nin severe terms.\nWednesday.\nWashington. Jan. 9. Little busi\nness was transacted by the house yes\nterday. After a forty-minute debate a\nrule was adopted giving the bill to re\nvise codify and amend the laws the\nright of way along with other prefer\nred measures. The bill was immedi\nately taken up and upon the conclu\nsion of its reading was laid aside to\npermit Mr. Gaines of Tennessee to ad\ndress the house in favor of an appro\npriation for \u2019The Hermitage,\u201d the\nhome of Andrew Jackson, near Nash\nville, Tenn.\nThursday.\nWashington, Jan. 10 -The Brown\nson affair was the chief topic of dis\ncussion in the senate yesterday. It\nwas brought up when Senator Hale ex\nplained the navy personnel bill which\nwas introduced by him. The presen\ntation of the bill led Senator Tillman\nro ask whether members of the com\nmittee would have an opportunity to\nnet facts in relation to the controversy\nover the Hrownson affair. Mr. Tillman\nminiated that he wished to call before\n'he committee witnesses to testify\n'\u2022encerning this matter. Mr. Hale re\nulie.l that he thought there would he\n10 obstacle to allowing the senator to\ndo that.\nAmid scenes of confusion the mem\ners of the bouse of representatives\nparticipated in a lottery for rooms in\ntiie new house office building opposite\nthe capitol. Outside of passing two\nbridge bills the assignment of quarters\nwas the only business transacted.\nFriday.\nWashington, Jan. 11 The house of\nrepresentatives yesterday resumed its\nold activity and for over five hours\ntransacted business of public nature.\nMaterial progress was made with the\nbill to codify, revise and amend the\ncriminal laws of tiie United States.\nAn attempt by Mr. Littlefield of\nMaine to amend the bill so as to af\nford protection to aliens in the matter\nof .civil rights failed by a decisive vote\nafter considerable discussion.\nThe feature of the session was a\nbrief address by Mr. Burleson of Tex\nas, who credited Senator Foraker and\nother Republicans with having charg\ned the president with responsibility\nfor the recent financial panic.\nARE TOO BUSY IN LAND CASES.\nColorado Congressman Makes an At-\ntack on the Administration.\nWashlngton, Jan. 14. \u2014In a personal\nletter which he addressed to the presi\ndent, the vice president. Speaker Can\nnon and all members of congress, the\njustices of the supreme court, mem\nbers of the president's cabinet and the\nWashington newspaper correspond\nents, George W. Cook, Republican con\ngressman at large from Colorado, se\nverely arraigns tbe administration for\nits course in prosecuting alleged in\nfractions of the public land laws in\nColoroda.\nCongressman Cook insists that great\ninjustice has been done to a number\nof Colorado's most honorable, upright\nand law abiding business men, in\nthat they have been unnecessarily\nbranded as criminals through over\nzealousnes\u00df of the government in or\ndering indictments without furnishing\nproper evidence.\nHe cites the recent decision of Fed\neral Judge Robert E. Lewis at Denver,\nin which he quashed the indictments\nagainst some thirty citizens, to show\nthat government prosecutors were\noveractive in their efforts to punish\nland frauds.\nPOISON IN MEAT.\nThree Children in Washburn, Wie.,\nMade Deathly Sick.\nWashburn. Wis., Jan. 14. The eat\ning of tanned meats came near being\ndisastrous for the entire family of Gus\nIlranston of this city, and it was\nthought for a time that some deaths\nwould occur from poisoning. The time\nly arrival of physicians was all that\nsaved the lives of the three children.\nAll are now getting along nicely, and\nIt is not thought that any serious re\nsults will follow.\nO\u2019BRIEN HELPING THE JAPS\nAMBASSADOR IS NOT FORCING\nWILY MIKADO TO SIGN THE\nPAPERS.\nWashington, Jan. 12. Considering\nthe smartness with which exchanges\nare progressing between America and\nJapan, relative to the adjustment of\nquestions growing out of the Immigra\ntion of Japanese laborers Into the\nUnited States, the officials of the state\ndepartment are puzzled to account for\nthe publication in various foreign cap\nitals, as well as in this country, of re\nports calculated to convey the impres\nsion that there is serious friction be\ntween the two countries over this sub\nject.\nThe latest of these reports that the\nJapanese foreign office Is reluctant to\naccede to a \u201cdemand\u201d of Ambassador\nO\u2019Brien that an agreement to restrict\nJapanese coolie immigration into the\nUnited States be reduced to writing,\nmeets with unqualified contradiction\nat the state department.\nNo Treaty Wanted.\nMr. O\u2019Brien is- merely aiding the\nJapanese officials to perfect interna\ntional regulations tbit will serve to\nstop the indiscriminate immigration\nevil. He is not expected to negotiate\nany treaty with Japan on this subject,\nor even to secure a modus vivendi, or\nanything in the nature of the written\nagreement referred to in some of the\npress dispatches.\nHe has, under Instructions from the\nstate department, acquainted the Jap\nanese government with the fact that\nthe measures adopted in Japan last\nspring, following the undertaking of\nthe Japanese government to restrict\nundesirable immigration to the United\nStates by a careful regulation of the\nissue of passports, have proved utterly\nineffective.\nJapanese Amazed.\nThe Japanese officials were sur\nprised at the figures presented by Mr.\nO\u2019Brien illustrating not only the con\ntinuance of the coolie immigration\ninto America, but its startling in\ncrease, even after the adoption of the\nJapanese restrictive policy.\nTherefore these Japanese officials\nhave been endeavoring to frame regu\nlations that shall be effective and in\nthe course of that effort they have nat\nurally communicated freely with the\nAmerican ambassador.\nNEW YORK FIRE FATAL TO FIVE\nFiremen Are Caught by Falling Floors\nand Tumbling Walls.\nNew York. Jan. 12. Four firemen\nwent to their deaths last night when\n(hey responded to a fire that ruined\nthe Parker building, a twelve-story\nbusiness structure, occupying the\nblock between East Eighteenth and\nNineteenth streets, on Fourth avenue.\nFought by half the firemen of Man\nhattan and apparatus that blocked the\nstreets for blocks, the flames were\nnever controlled and only with diffi\nculty were confined to the building in\nwhich they originated. Floor after\nfloor gave way and dropped to the\nbasement, and beneath these and\ncrumbling walls no less than thirty\nfiremen were caught and either killed\noutright or seriously injured.\nFour Fail to Respond.\nWhen the fire had burned itself out\nand the firemen's roll was called four\nmen failed to respond.\nOne fireman was removed, dying, to\nthe hospital, and two others were dan\ngerously hurt.\nThe monetary loss was estimated at\n$5,000,000. The fire was one of the\nmost spectacular as well as disas\ntrous in recent years. From start to\nfinish its course was marked by heart\nrending scenes, sensational escapes\nand acts of heroism.\nSpectacular Rescue.\nOn the top floor, in the Suffolk En\ngraving company\u2019s establishment, six\nmen were working. Their escape was\ncut off and they fled to the roof.\nFlames had surrounded them on three\nsides, and they were in imminent\ndanger of death when rescued by\nmeans of a life line shot from a mor\ntar gun and manned by a hook and\nladder company on the roof of the\nFlorence building adjoining. Down\nthis rope, hand over hand, the six men\ndropped to safety\nRetreat It Cut Off.\nSeven firemen ran np to the fifth\nfloor of the building after extension\nladders had oeen raised to the win\ndows of that story to make possible\nthe firemen\u2019s retreat. After a fruitless\neffort to stay the flames at the place\nof origin the firemen were driven to\nthe windows, only to find that the\ntops of the ladders had been burned,\ncutting off their only retreat. Three\nof the sever made a desperate effort\nto reach the roof. They were not\nseen again, and are supposed to be\ndead in the ruins. The other four\nwere rescued by men who at the risk\nof their own lives ran up scaling lad\nders and dragged the more or less\nburned firemen from the windows.\nSwitchman la Killed.\nSt. Paul, Jan. 12. \u2014B. Beselves was\nkilled in the Minnesota Transfer rail\nway yards yesterday while switching.\nHe was knocked down and the wheels\nof two cars passed over him.\nSeeks Death Under Train.\nNewark. N. J., Jan. 12. \u2014Mrs. Henry\nO. Boeme of Orange, N. J., committed\nsuicide yesterday by kneeling In front\nof an express train on the Lackawan\nna railroad as it was approaching\nRoseville. Mrs. Boehme w.a mentally\nderanged.\u2019\nLad Kills a Burglar.\nGreensburg, Pa., Jan. 12. Paul\nBowers, fourteen years old, shot and\nkilled a negro burglar who broke into\nthe home of his father at Alrerton,\nnear here.\nfitPif I\n\nThe\nGeneral Demand\nof the Well-Infonned of the World has\nalways been for a simple, pleasant and\nefficient liquid laxative remedy of known\nvalue; a laxative which physicians could\nsauction for family use because its com\nponent parts are known to them to be\nwholesome and truly beneficial in effect,\nacceptable to the system and gentle, yet\nprompt, in action.\nIn supplying that demand with its ex\ncellent combination of Syrup of Figs and\nElixir of Senna, the California Fig Syrup\nCo. proceeds along ethical lines and relies\non the merits of the laxative for its remark\nable success.\nThat is oue of many reasons why\nSyrup of Figs and Elixir of Senna is given\nthe preference by the Well-Informed.\nTo \u2018get its beneficial effects always buy\nthe genuine\u2014manufactured by the Cali\nfornia Fig Syrup Co., only, and for sals\nby all leading druggists. Price fifty cents\nper bottle.\nA Sometime Paradox.\n\"Debonair is one of those genial\nphilosophers whom nothing seems able\nto disturb. He takes even trouble\nwith equanimity.\u201d\n\"Yes, to see his manners when he is\nlaid up sick in bed, you can say of him\nliterally that he is perfectly natural\nand ill at ease at the same time.\"\nWhy Ask?\n\"What did you do on your last auto\nmobile tour?\u201d\n\"Swallowed dust and spent money.\u201d\nIt\u2019s Kind.\n\"There Is something very funny, af\nter all. In the situation In Georgia.\"\n\u2018lt Is all dry humor, then.\u201d\nMany Professional Men,\nClergymen, teachers and singers use\nBrown\u2019s Bronchial Troches for curing\nhoarseness and coughs.\nIf a political candidate is unable to\nwork the voters, he\u2019ll have to work at\nsomething else.\nPILES CURED IN TO 14 DATS.\nPAZO OINTMENT U guaranteed to cure any cam\nof Itching, Blind. Bleeding or I'rotradiug l*ue\u00ab la\n\u2022to 14 days or money refunded. bOc-\nThe selfish feast shows the famish\ned heart\nffrSSOASTIM\nHi j'ASTORIjThe Kind You Have\nP Always Bought\n\u25a0|UtJ ALCOHOL 3 PER CENT.\nAYegelabte PrepaniionforAs ri\n13 fisssaaggs Bears the n\n111 IKWiMaMIIj Signature\nPromotesDigcstionJChmful- A A f\nIS c ness and Rest. Contains neither vl Ml\\ IU\n1 i Opium .Morphine nor Mineral. #llll r\nNot Narc otic, j Iyl Yi\nInluk fjttxSmna e j I\nBf 1 JkMteSM- TH 111\nMb sited- 1 li P\nif /w a/* US 6\nbE-q lion. Sour Stomach.Dtarrtm 1 Ifcf m\n\u25a0Eanir Worms,Convulsions,fVv'erisli M LH K 11 If Ql*\nRrg ness and Loss OF Sleep. \\J* IUI UVul\nmwSs\u00dfm Th r TeafS\nGASTORIA\nExact Copy of Wrapper. Wl ef WT g co WT 0 s\u00ab errv.\nlember*or tm eVJKtS- 8 o\nMEN. BOV, WOMEN, MIBBEB AND CHILDREN. tit 1 B\nthan any othaa manufaotaama In Tr\nV. AoHflss $4 and $5 Gilt Edge Shoes Cannot Bo Equalled At Any Price /rxny<..\u00ab/ v\n.ari'AVTIORt. W. L. Douglas namt and pries It ctsmpsd on bottom. Tnk\u00bb No Mnh\u00abtltut\u00ab,\nSold by the best shoe dealers ncmrb